<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many 4x8 sheets for a floor?", answer: "Divide the floor area (length × width) by 32 (the square feet of one 4x8 sheet) and round up. A 20 × 10 ft room is 200 sq ft, so 200 ÷ 32 = 6.25 → 7 sheets. Add 5 to 10 percent for waste on complex cuts, making 8 sheets a safe buy. The same math works for roof sheathing and wall sheathing." },
  { question: "Is a 4x8 sheet really 4 by 8 feet?", answer: "Yes — plywood and OSB are sold at full 4-foot by 8-foot dimensions, not the reduced 'nominal' size that applies to dimensional lumber. A 4x8 sheet covers exactly 32 square feet. Metric versions sold outside North America are the same size rounded to 1.22 × 2.44 meters." },
  { question: "What is the difference between plywood and OSB?", answer: "Plywood is made of thin wood veneers glued in cross-laminated layers. OSB (oriented strand board) is made of wood chips compressed with resin. OSB is cheaper and usually stronger in shear, so it is the standard for wall sheathing, roof sheathing, and subfloors. Plywood is preferred where moisture exposure is a concern (e.g. exposed decking) and for finish work. Both use the same 4x8 sheet size." },
  { question: "What thickness plywood for subfloor?", answer: "3/4 inch tongue-and-groove plywood or OSB over 16\" OC joists is the residential standard for most floor loads. Use 7/8\" or 1-1/8\" over 19.2\" or 24\" OC joists, or where heavy finishes (tile, stone) are planned. For roof sheathing, 5/8\" is typical at 24\" OC rafter spacing, or 1/2\" at 16\" OC." },
  { question: "How do I minimize waste when cutting plywood?", answer: "Plan the layout so full sheets cover the majority of the surface and cuts fall near edges where they can be used for other sections. Stagger joints between rows. Draw a cut diagram before you start — it often reduces waste from 10 percent to under 5 percent, saving one or two sheets on larger projects." }
]) %>

