    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How the Plywood Sheets Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        The math is simple: <strong>sheets needed = ceiling(total area ÷ sheet area × (1 + waste factor))</strong>. A 4×8 sheet covers 32 sq ft, a 4×10 covers 40 sq ft, and a 5×10 covers 50 sq ft. The calculator divides your surface area by the chosen sheet area, adds the waste percentage, and rounds up to the nearest whole sheet. It also shows the "full sheets" count (no waste) so you can see the raw minimum before waste allowance.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Sheet Sizes Available</h2>
      <p>
        The default <strong>4 × 8 ft</strong> sheet is the universal residential standard and fits every 16" OC framing layout. <strong>4 × 10 ft</strong> sheets reduce seams on taller walls and ceilings and are useful for commercial gypsum work. <strong>5 × 10 ft</strong> oversize sheets are made for industrial floor panels and certain commercial sheathing jobs — they need special handling but reduce joints on large surfaces. Outside North America the same 4×8 sheet is sold at 1.22 × 2.44 meters.
      </p>

      <h3>Thickness Selection</h3>
      <p>
        Common plywood/OSB thicknesses: <strong>1/4"</strong> for cabinet backs and paneling, <strong>3/8"</strong> for light sheathing, <strong>1/2"</strong> for wall sheathing and roof decking at 16" OC, <strong>5/8"</strong> for roof decking at 24" OC, <strong>3/4"</strong> tongue-and-groove for subfloors over 16-19.2" OC joists, and <strong>7/8"</strong> or <strong>1-1/8"</strong> for heavy subfloor loads or 24" OC joists. Match thickness to your framing spacing and expected load.
      </p>

      <h3>Waste Allowance</h3>
      <p>
        For a simple rectangular surface with minimal cuts (rectangular floor, clean roof), use 5 percent waste. For walls with windows and doors, roofs with dormers and valleys, or irregular shapes with many cutouts, use 10 to 15 percent. A good cut list drawn before you start reduces waste significantly — draw every sheet on paper with the cuts needed, and try to use offcuts for smaller pieces elsewhere in the project.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How much does a 4x8 sheet cover?</h3>
      <p>Exactly 32 square feet (2.97 m²) of continuous flat surface.</p>

      <h3>What is T&G plywood?</h3>
      <p>Tongue-and-groove plywood has shaped edges that interlock between sheets, reducing squeaks and eliminating the need for blocking at joints. Required for most subfloors.</p>

      <h3>Can I use OSB for everything plywood does?</h3>
      <p>Almost — OSB is not ideal for decking exposed to repeated wetting, for finish surfaces, or for cabinet interiors. For structural sheathing and subfloors, OSB is cheaper and equally strong.</p>

      <h3>How do plywood grades work?</h3>
      <p>Grades are A (best face) to D (roughest), combined like AA, AB, CD. CDX is common construction grade (C one face, D other face, exterior glue).</p>

      <h3>What does "underlayment grade" mean?</h3>
      <p>Thin (1/4" or 3/8") plywood used over a structural subfloor to provide a smooth surface for vinyl, linoleum, or tile. Has a sanded face and no voids.</p>

